{
  "text": "Rain gauge data are known to have errors (both systematic and random) with possible effects from obstruction, wind, wetting, splashing, evaporation and calibration [CITATION_1] . The windinduced error is the primary source of a systematic error that increases with an increase in wind speed [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . As such, the wind-related error will be large during the passage of TCs and this has to be taken into consideration when comparing with TMPA. Accurate observations during extreme weather conditions are further difficult as there is a chance of some degree of uncertainty and propagation of gross, systematic and random errors due to instrumental malfunction during such weather conditions. Nonetheless, gauge data are still considered to be the most accurate and direct measurement of rainfall and the optimal choice for evaluation of satellite precipitation estimates [CITATION_5] Chen et al., 2013b, c) .",
